Title: Information Retrieval from a Vast Repository of Complex Data  
Abstract: NASA has terabytes of multimedia data for exploration of Space Science, Atmospheric Science, Flight Dynamics, Life Sciences, and other related fields of science. This data is available in electronic and other forms. Scientists and the general public including students should be able to use it in learning and scientific research. The task of accessing this data can be made simple by using a variety of user interfaces and the notion digital libraries. A digital library contains text, images, and sound in an integrated document repository. Digital libraries can be networked to give users (local/remote) access to a vast amount of data, information, knowledge, and vision. The concept of digital libraries can be realized by enhancing and integrating technologies in databases, communication networks, user interfaces, knowledge management, and information retrieval. A digital library containing the NASA data like satellite images, global change data, data from space shuttle or space station experiments can be built taking advantage of research advances in graphics, window-based systems, and ATM (Asynchronous Transfer Mode) networks for high bandwidth communication. Our research will contribute in managing the NASA databases so that a variety of users can retrieve it in various degrees of detail and depth. Users should be able to locate relevant data without searching the entire information repository. Users may know approximately what data they need but might not be able to specify their needs precisely. They may not initially know exactly what data is available and needed. But if the system can interactively assist the users in getting the right data and information they will be able to increase their scientific knowledge. To help them, a retrieval based on content and imprecise queries should be supported. Existing indexing schemes are too rigid and do not support retrieval based on semantic content of information. We propose to develop techniques that will allow the user to specify a query based on her partial knowledge of the content and route her query to the appropriate information base. We propose to develop techniques for content-based retrieval of images and other multimedia data in addition to text. We will propose new algorithms and techniques in the area of digital library management and develop a prototype to demonstrate the implementation of a NASA digital library. 
