Reference-contexts: The Wide Area Information Server system (WAIS), which uses the Z39.50 standard as its basis, supports traditional text search, mostly index based. A WAIS user has to scroll through a long list of servers to locate a server which contains the desired kind of information <ref> [3] </ref>. WAIS has the ability to handle non-textual data, but this capacity is currently being used to a very limited extent. For example, some images can only be retrieved by providing the name of the file in which the image is stored. World-Wide Web facilitates hypermedia access across the Internet. <p> In the following subsections we present existing retrieval schemes and study their suitability for implementation in a digital library. The schemes are presented in increasing order of complexity. Information retrieval techniques can be divided into three classes: tag-based retrieval, partial content-based retrieval and full content-based retrieval <ref> [3] </ref>. 3.1 Tag-Based Retrieval When data objects are added to the information base, a human expert has to provide a set of keywords to represent the object. The information retrieval system uses this information as an index to retrieve data. The data objects themselves are never inspected by the system. <p> There is thus a conflict between desire for thorough information retrieval and the desire for tight, efficient access structures. The limits of information retrieval are attained by full-content based methods <ref> [3] </ref>. These methods use no access structures whatsoever. The entire data object can be used for retrieval. No information is omitted from the search.
